Best fix

Make the row selection deterministic by adding a tie-breaker in both the view and the validation query.

For example:

ROW_NUMBER() OVER (
    PARTITION BY ED.MBI
    ORDER BY 
        EE.UPDATEDATE DESC,
        CASE WHEN UPPER(EE.EMAIL_INVALID_IND) = 'INVALID' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END ASC,
        EE.EMAILADDRESS
)

That does this:

latest update date first
if tied, prefer VALID over INVALID
if still tied, sort by email address

If you want to prefer INVALID instead, flip that CASE ordering.

Important note about your view

Your view has SELECT DISTINCT plus ROW_NUMBER(). Usually DISTINCT is not needed here, because ROW_NUMBER() ... QUALIFY = 1 already keeps one row per partition. It usually does not cause this exact issue, but removing unnecessary DISTINCT can make debugging easier.

What to tell your manager

